\subsection{Frobenius closed parameter ideals III}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a local ring of characteristic $p>0$. In order to show that $R$ is $F$-injective, it is necessary to consider all local cohomology modules, while it suffices to consider all local cohomology modules except for the top one to check the Buchsbaumness on $R$. It thus seems natural to pose the following question.




\begin{question}\label{gtakagi}
Let $(R, {\frak{m}},k)$ be a reduced $F$-finite generalized Cohen-Macaulay local ring. Suppose that the Frobenius acts on $H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ injectively for all $i<d$. Then is $R$ Buchsbaum?
\end{question}


We will work with the finiteness dimension, in which the following lemma plays a role. Its proof is the adoptation of that of \cite[Theorem 3.4]{Tr86}.


\begin{lemma}
\label{standardcri}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a local ring and let ${\frak{a}} \subseteq R$ be an ${\frak{m}}$-primary ideal. Let $s \le f_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ be an integer. Then the following are equivalent.

\begin{enumerate}
\item
The canonical map $H^i({\frak{a}};R) \to H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is surjective for all $i < s$.

\item
Every filter regular sequence $x_1, \ldots, x_s \in {\frak{a}}$ is standard on $R$.

\item
The ideal ${\frak{a}}$ has a set of generators $\{a_1, \ldots, a_n\}$ such that for every subset $J$ of $\{1, \ldots, n\}$ with $\sharp J=s$, we have that $\{a_j \, | \, j \in J\}$ forms a filter regular sequence (in any order) and this sequence is standard.
\end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}


As observed from the discussions after Theorem \ref{finitedim}, it is not true that any filter regular sequence of $R$ of length $s$ generates a Frobenius closed ideal when the Frobenius action on $H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is injective for all $i \le s$. However, we have the following theorem.


\begin{theorem}
\label{injec imply stand}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a reduced $F$-finite local ring with $f_{{\frak{m}}}(R) =t \ge 1$ and let $s \le t$ be a positive integer. Suppose that the Frobenius action is injective on $H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ for all $i<s$. Then every filter regular sequence of length $s$ of $R$ is standard.
\end{theorem}


\begin{proof}
Put $n=\dim_k {\frak{m}}/{\frak{m}}^2$. By Lemma \ref{basisfilter}, we can choose a set of generators $\{a_1,\ldots,a_n\}$ of ${\frak{m}}$ such that for every subset $J$ of $\{1,\ldots, n\}$ with $\sharp J=s$, we have that $\{a_j \, | \, j \in J\}$ forms a filter regular sequence (in any order) of both $R$ and $R^{1/p}/R$. By Theorem \ref{finitedim}, we see that $a_1, \ldots, a_{s-1}$ is a standard sequence and the ideal $(a_1, \ldots, a_{i})$ is Frobenius closed for all $i<s$. Using the technique of \cite[Proposition 3.3]{M15}, $a_1, \ldots, a_s$ is also a standard sequence.
Now the theorem follows from Lemma \ref{standardcri}.
\end{proof}


We obtain the following corollary as an affirmative answer to Question \ref{gtakagi}.


\begin{corollary}
\label{takagi}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a reduced $F$-finite generalized Cohen-Macaulay local ring with $d=\dim R$. Suppose the Frobenius action on $H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is injective for all $i<d$. Then $R$ is Buchsbaum.
\end{corollary}


Note that the Buchsbaumness can be characterized in terms of the canonical map ${\operatorname{Ext}}^i(k,-) \to H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(-)$ (cf. \cite[Corollary 2.16]{SV86}) or by the truncated dualizing complex (cf. \cite[Theorem 2.3]{Sc82}). We need the following generalization for the finiteness dimension. For the details of the truncated dualizing complex $\tau^{>-s}\omega^{\bullet}_R$  and $\tau^{<s}\mathbf{R}\Gamma_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$, see \cite{Sc82} and \cite{BMS16}.


\begin{lemma}
\label{dualizing complex}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a local ring and let $s \le f_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ be an integer. Then the following are equivalent.

\begin{enumerate}
\item
Every filter regular sequence $x_1, \ldots, x_s$ of $R$ is standard.

\item
The canonical map $H^i({\frak{m}};R) \to H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is surjective for all $i < s$.
\end{enumerate}
Suppose that there is a surjective ring map $(A,{\frak{m}}, k) \twoheadrightarrow (R,{\frak{m}},k)$ with $A$ regular. Then the above conditions are equivalent to each of the following conditions.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(a)]
The canonical map ${\operatorname{Ext}}^i_A(k,R) \to H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is surjective for all $i< s$.

\item[(b)]
The $\tau^{<s}\mathbf{R}\Gamma_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is quasi-isomorphic to a complex of $k$-vector spaces.

\item[(c)]
The $\tau^{>-s}\omega^{\bullet}_R$ is quasi-isomorphic to a complex of $k$-vector spaces.
\end{enumerate}


\end{lemma}


\begin{proof}
The statements $(b)$ and $(c)$ are dual to each other. The lemma follows from Lemma \ref{standardcri}, \cite[Corollary 3.6]{Tr86} and \cite[Lemma 3.7]{BMS16}.
\end{proof}


The following theorem is a recent result of Bhatt, Ma and Schwede in \cite[Main Theorem A, Theorem 3.4]{BMS16}. While their proof is based on difficult techniques of Bhatt and Scholze (cf. \cite{BSc15}), our proof is elementary.


\begin{theorem}
\label{bhatt-ma-schwede}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a reduced $F$-finite local ring with $f_{{\frak{m}}}(R)=t \ge 1$ and let $0 <s \le t$ be an integer. Suppose that the Frobenius action on $H^i_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is injective for all $i<s$. Then $\tau^{>-s}\omega^{\bullet}_R$ is quasi-isomorphic to a complex of $k$-vector spaces. Equivalently, $\tau^{<s}\mathbf{R}\Gamma_{{\frak{m}}}(R)$ is quasi-isomorphic to a complex of $k$-vector spaces. In particular, these truncated complexes split into a direct sum of their cohomologies.
\end{theorem}


\begin{proof}
Just combine Theorem \ref{injec imply stand} and Lemma \ref{dualizing complex}.
\end{proof}



\subsection{The small Cohen-Macaulay module conjecture}
We close this section with a link between generalized Cohen-Macaulay $F$-injective rings and the small Cohen-Macaulay module conjecture of Hochster.


\begin{conjecture}[The small Cohen-Macaulay module conjecture]
\label{smallMC}
Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a complete local domain. Then $R$ admits a non-zero finitely generated module $M$ such that $\dim R={\operatorname{depth}} M$.
\end{conjecture}


Let $(R,{\frak{m}},k)$ be a complete local domain with $d=\dim R$. Assume that $d=2$. Then the small Cohen-Macaulay module conjecture is true by letting $M$ equal the integral closure of $R$ in the field of fractions of $R$. However, Conjecture \ref{smallMC} remains open in higher dimensional case. In the case $d=3$, Hartshorne, Hochster, and Peskine and Szpiro independently proved that if $R$ is an $\mathbb{N}$-graded finitely generated domain over a perfect field $R_0=K$ of characteristic $p>0$, then $R$ has a graded maximal Cohen-Macaulay module \cite[pages 224, 225]{ILL07}. In fact, we have the following stronger result (cf. \cite[Exercise 21.25]{ILL07}).


\begin{theorem}
\label{T5.15}
